Good afternoon,

I am attempting to transfer a custom token from Account A to Account B using a transaction created by Account C. I have spent quite some time on this problem, and tried different approaches. As such, I am writing this question.


Consider the following code:

```
        const claimBountyTxn: Mina.Transaction = await Mina.transaction(
          interactor2PublicKey, () => {
            AccountUpdate.fundNewAccount(interactor2PublicKey, 1);
            bbbSC.claimBounty(interactor1PublicKey);
          });

        await claimBountyTxn.prove();
        claimBountyTxn.sign([interactor2PrivateKey]);
        await claimBountyTxn.send();
```

In this code, a token managed by `bbbSC` should be transferred from the `interactor1PublicKey` (Account A) to `interactor2PrivateKey.toPublicKey()` (Account B). In this case, Account C = Account B, but it could've been a different account. Account A is always different from account B and it cannot participate in the signing of data.

Curretnly, I am getting the following error:

```

    Transaction failed with errors:
    - Check signature: Invalid signature on account_update 5 for key B62qmHhLqZSxyRcYDbG33PqYZ9x1E42TCD3CGuhNVPQpRPmdtnmCKmY

    > 356 |         await claimBountyTxn.send();
```

`B62qmHhLqZSxyRcYDbG33PqYZ9x1E42TCD3CGuhNVPQpRPmdtnmCKmY`  = Account A, i.e. the account from which the custom token is being tranferred to.

(CHARACTER LIMIT! CONTINUING IN COMMENTS)

Below is the relevant code of the token owner smart contract:

```
export class BountyBulletinBoardContract extends TokenContract {


  deploy(args: DeployArgs) {
    super.deploy(args);
    // Temporarily all set to proof, will be refined later
    this.account.permissions.set({
      ...Permissions.default(),
      editState: Permissions.proof(),
      setTokenSymbol: Permissions.proof(),
      send: Permissions.none(),
      receive: Permissions.none(),
      access: Permissions.proofOrSignature(),
    });

  }

  @method approveBase(forest: AccountUpdateForest) {
    // Purposefully a condition that evaluates to True. This is by desing (for now).
    forest.isEmpty().assertFalse();
  }

  @method sendFromTo(
    senderAddress: PublicKey,
    receiverAddress: PublicKey,
    amount: UInt64
  ) {

    let accountUpdate = this.internal.send({
      from: senderAddress,
      to:receiverAddress,
      amount: amount,
    });

    this.approveAccountUpdate(accountUpdate); // I don't believe this is needed!
  }

  @method claimBounty(
    funderAddress: PublicKey
  ) {
    let au = AccountUpdate.create(funderAddress, this.deriveTokenId());
    let balance: UInt64 = au.account.balance.getAndRequireEquals();
    this.sendFromTo(bountyPublicKey, this.sender, balance);
  }
```

What am I doing wrong here and how can the problem be solved? Am I misunderstanding how account updates should be authorized?

Thank you!

Here a snippet of the the failing account update:

```
"body": {
        "publicKey": "B62qoSmesNDDCx61zCpdoWWheaLteTA2yTRLzGWyvXjqrfZuF43Dgng",
        "tokenId": "xtMCsQWRBe5pJsaykYbyM8i76LF5FfncT8NKAU1165wRgrRWF4",
        "update": {
          ..
        "balanceChange": {
          "magnitude": "10",
          "sgn": "Negative"
        },
        "incrementNonce": false,
        ..
        "mayUseToken": {
          "parentsOwnToken": true,
          "inheritFromParent": false
        },
        "authorizationKind": {
          "isSigned": true,
          "isProved": false,
          "verificationKeyHash": "3392518251768960475377392625298437850623664973002200885669375116181514017494"
        }
      },
      "authorization": {
        "proof": null,
        "signature": "7mWxjLYgbJUkZNcGouvhVj5tJ8yu9hoexb9ntvPK8t5LHqzmrL6QJjjKtf5SgmxB4QWkDw7qoMMbbNGtHVpsbJHPyTy2EzRQ"
      }
```

It appears that a proof is not attached? The signature is there, but it wouldn't be the one from Account A (the account from which the tokens are being sent).

I also have this version, which. results in `update_not_permitted_balance` error. From what I understand, this is due to the fact that I'm not signing the transaction with `Account A`'s private key, but my goal is to avoid doing exactly that.

Here is the version in question:

```
@method claimBounty(
    funderAddress: PublicKey,
    bountyId: UInt64,
  ) {
    // 1. Derive the  a PublicKey, which will represent the address of the account 
    // which contains the bounty to be claimed
    const bountyPublicKey: PublicKey = this.deriveBountyAccountAddressMethod(funderAddress, bountyId);

    let au = AccountUpdate.create(bountyPublicKey, this.deriveTokenId());
    let balance: UInt64 = au.account.balance.getAndRequireEquals();
    au.balance.subInPlace(balance);
    au.body.mayUseToken = AccountUpdate.MayUseToken.ParentsOwnToken;
    this.approve(au);

    let au2 = AccountUpdate.create(this.sender, this.deriveTokenId());
    au2.balance.addInPlace(balance);
    au2.body.mayUseToken = AccountUpdate.MayUseToken.ParentsOwnToken;
    this.approve(au2);   
  }
```

While we're on the topic, it's not fully clear to me  what `au2.body.mayUseToken = AccountUpdate.MayUseToken.ParentsOwnToken;` is supposed to do.

Hello, and thanks for replying @Faserisko .


> What you want to do instead, set the permission of the user's token account when it's created.
I will need to deploy a new smart contract for that, correct? Is there any way not to deploy an extra contract? Isn't the user's token account the (public key, token ID) pair? How would I set permissions on that?

> This sets the authorisation to the signature, which you are trying to avoid.
Does that mean that this.internal.send() sets the auth to signature? How would one transfer without it? I tried manual account updates, and it didn't work. When I try to do account updates from the outside (2 Account Updates: one from the sender, one from the receiver), it repots that the Transaction is too expensive:

```
        const claimBountyTxn: Mina.Transaction = await Mina.transaction(
          interactor2PublicKey, () => {
            AccountUpdate.fundNewAccount(interactor2PublicKey, 1);

            let au1 = AccountUpdate.create(confirmedFundedPubKey, bbbSC.deriveTokenId());

            let balance: UInt64 = au1.account.balance.getAndRequireEquals();
            au1.balance.subInPlace(balance);
            bbbSC.approveUpdate(au1);

            let au2 = AccountUpdate.create(interactor2PublicKey, bbbSC.deriveTokenId());
            au2.balance.addInPlace(balance);
            bbbSC.approveUpdate(au2);
          });
```

Thank you again, any feedback on this is extremely valuable, as I've run of available resources on this: already ready through all of the existing GitHub code, but none of it appears to be doing what I need to do 😄

> Additionally, you can set the verification key to the token account to implement any additional logic that is required for transfer or any other operation
@DFST Could you please expand a little on where I should be looking for this? The link that you sent is to `nft.sell()`. I'm assuming I should be looking here:

```
async internalSell(params: SellParams, fee: UInt64) {
    const { address, price } = params;
    const sender = this.sender.getAndRequireSignature();
    const ownerUpdate = AccountUpdate.createSigned(sender);
    ownerUpdate.send({ to: wallet, amount: fee });
    const tokenId = this.deriveTokenId();
    const nft = new NFTContract(address, tokenId);
    await nft.sell(price);
  }
```
I also checked the code of `NFTContract`:

```

  async deploy(args: DeployArgs) {
    super.deploy(args);
    this.account.permissions.set({
      ...Permissions.default(),
      editState: Permissions.proof(),
    });
  }
```

Where is the verification key set?

I think you mean this part, in the first link:

```
update.body.update.verificationKey = {
      isSome: Bool(true),
      value: data.verificationKey,
    };
```

It appears that in order to set permission on an account in the form of:

```

    const au: AccountUpdate = AccountUpdate.createSigned(<pub_key>, this.deriveTokenId());
    au.body.update.permissions = {
      isSome: Bool(true),
      value: {
        ...Permissions.default(),
        send: Permissions.none(),
      }
    }
```

The tranasction must be signed with the private key corresponding to `<pub_key>`, is that correct?

When I try to use AccountUpdate.create(...) it gives me `Update_not_permitted_permissions` error

Perhaps I'm misunderstanding something, but what I am trying to do is:

```
  async internalSell(params: SellParams, fee: UInt64) {
    const { address, price } = params;
    const sender = generateRandomPublicKey(); // <<<------------- here
    const ownerUpdate = AccountUpdate.createSigned(sender);
    ownerUpdate.send({ to: wallet, amount: fee });
    const tokenId = this.deriveTokenId();
    const nft = new NFTContract(address, tokenId);
    await nft.sell(price);
  }
```

Essentially, the send logic should transfer funds from a random public key, without having the corresponding private key to sign the transaction.

Imagine that `generateRandomPublicKey()` generates a random public key on every invocation [I'm not generating them randomly per se, but rather by hashing a Field value]

Thanks! What if I do something like this (draft code):

```
class SmartContractA extends SmartContract {
  @method deploySmartContractB(smartContractBAddress: PublicKey) {
    // Create an instance of SmartContractB
    const smartContractB = new SmartContractB(smartContractBAddress);

    // Deploy SmartContractB
    smartContractB.deploy();

    // Retrieve the account update of SmartContractB
    const smartContractBUpdate = smartContractB.self;

    // Approve the account update of SmartContractB
    this.approve(smartContractBUpdate, AccountUpdate.Layout.AnyChildren);

    // Additional checks can be added here to verify the specific type or properties of SmartContractB
    // E.g.: check the verification key of SmartContractB
    const expectedVerificationKey = "..."; // verification key of SmartContractB
    const actualVerificationKey = smartContractB.getVerificationKey();
    actualVerificationKey.assertEquals(expectedVerificationKey, "SmartContractB has an unexpected verification key");
  }
}
```

In this way, I believe I can ensure that the Smart Contract B is deployed. 

Now, let's say I also set the the .deployer state var of SmartContract B to this.sender. If I understand correctly, no matter who deploys Smart Contract B, the verification key must always be the same. So, wouldn't it be enough to just check for a hardcoded verification key of Smart Contract B, in the methods of Smart Contract A?
